\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 13. R. gouanii }Willd.,{\i  Sp. Pl. }{\b 2}({\b 2}): 1322 (1800). Pubescent. Rhizome apex with hairs 3-4 mm, usually with fibres. Cauline leaves usually semi-amplexicaul. Sepals rather densely pubescent. Honey-leaves 10-25 mm. Beak at least 1/3 as long as the achene, rigid. 2n = 16. •{\i  Pyrenees and Cordillera Cantabrica.} Ga Hs.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 14. R. ruscinonensis }Landolt,{\i  Ber. Schweiz. Bot. Ges.}{\b  66}: 101 (1956). Pubescent. Rhizome without hairs, usually without fibres at apex. Cauline leaves not amplexicaul. Sepals rather densely pubescent. Honey-leaves 8-15 mm. Beak c. 1/3 as long as the achene, rigid. 2n = 16. •{\i  C. & E. Pyrenees.} Ga Hs.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 15. R. sartorianus }Boiss. & Heldr. in Boiss.,{\i  Diagn. Pl. Or. Nov.}{\b  3}({\b 1}): 8 (1853). Like {\b 14} but sparsely pubescent to subglabrous; rhizome with fibres at apex; honey-leaves up to 20 mm. 2n = 16, 32.{\i  Italy and Balkan peninsula.} Al Bu Gr Ju.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 Plants from Appennini and the mountains of C. & S. Italy, like {\b 15} but with appressed-pubescent basal leaves, the segments of the single cauline leaf lanceolate, and the beak c. 1/5 as long as the achene have been called {\b R. apenninus} (Chiov.) Pignatti, {\i Gior. Bot. Ital. }{\b 116}: 94 (1983), and plants from the same area like {\b 15} but with the basal leaves more strongly pubescent have been called {\b R. pollinensis} (N. Terracc.) Chiov.,{\i  Bull. Soc. Bot. Ital.}{\b  1892}: 279 (1892); their status is uncertain.
